        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Because of the faintness of the source,
our strategy is to maximize the sensitivity of the array by proposing a
spatially unresolved observation with the most compact array
configuration. The object will be detected as point source, therefore a
discussion of the field-of-view, the resolvable scale and mosaic-imaging
can be neglected and the integrated continuum flux represents already the
faintest peak continuum flux.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_ANGULAR_RESOLUTION</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We propose to observe the thermal continuum emission of the disk around
OTS44 at 233 GHz (1.287 mm). OTS 44 is the least massive known object that
hosts a substantial disk, which has been confirmed at 70 micrometer by Herschel.
Through the low sensitivity of pre-ALMA instruments, no measurement
exists in the (sub)mm range. 

From the modelling of the disk presented in Joergens et al. (2013) 
the continuum flux in ALMA band 6 at 233 GHz is estimated to 0.0688 mJy
assuming almost no grain growth (grain sizes 2.5 micrometer). 
If we assume grain growth to sizes &gt; 250 micrometer, as seen for other 
substellar objects, a continuum flux in band 6 of &gt; 0.210 mJy is estimated. 
In a very pessimistic and unrealistic case of interstellar-medium (ISM) 
grain sizes (0.25 micrometer) the continuum flux in band 6 is estimated 
to 0.0344 mJy. 

To achieve a signal to noise ratio of at least 6 in the case of almost no 
grain growth (2.5 micrometer grain sizes), the necessary sensitivity is 
0.011 mJy, corresponding to an on-source time of 2.6 h.
In the likely case of grain growth to &gt; 250 micrometer, we will achieve 
a SNR of &gt; 19 with these observations and in the very pessimistic case 
of ISM-like grains a SNR of 3.
Including all overheads and calibrator source observations the required
total time for this science goal is ~4.4 h.

Besides the estimation of the observing time with the ALMA sensitivity
calculator, we simulated a synthetic ALMA observation with CASA 4.2 (Fig. 3). 
This simulation includes the influence of thermal and phase noise through of
the water vapour in the atmosphere by PWV = (1.262 +- 0.15) mm. It shows
the feasibility of the proposed observation and a sufficient u-v coverage.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_SENSITIVITY</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
