        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We propose to observe the thermal continuum emission of the disk around
OTS44 at 405 GHz (0.740 mmm). OTS 44 is the least massive known object that
hosts a substantial disk, which has been confirmed at 70 micrometer by Herschel.
Through the low sensitivity of pre-ALMA instruments, no measurement exists 
in the (sub)mm range. 

From the modelling of the disk presented in Joergens et al. (2013)
the continuum flux in ALMA band 8 at 405 GHz is estimated to 0.4478 mJy 
assuming almost no grain growth (grain sizes of 2.5 micrometer). 
If we assume grain growth to sizes &gt; 250 micrometer as seen for other 
substellar objects, a continuum flux in band 8 of &gt; 1.079 mJy is estimated. 
In a very pessimistic and unrealistic case of interstellar-medium (ISM) 
grain sizes (0.25 micrometer) the continuum flux in ALMA is predicted 
to 0.224 mJy. 

To achieve a signal-to-noise ratio of at least 6 in the case of almost no
grain growth (2.5 micrometer grain size), the necessary sensitivity is 
0.0733 mJy, corresponding to an on-source time of ~1 h. 
In the likely case of grain growth to &gt; 250 micrometer, we will achieve 
a SNR of &gt; 15 with these observations and in the very pessimistic case 
of ISM-like grains a SNR of 3. 
Including all overheads and calibrator source observations the required 
total time for this science goal is 2.0 h.

Besides the estimation of the observing time with the ALMA sensitivity
calculator, we simulated a synthetic ALMA observation with CASA 4.2 (Fig. 3). 
This simulation includes the influence of thermal and phase noise through of
the water vapour in the atmosphere by PWV = (1.262 +- 0.15) mm. It shows
the feasibility of the proposed observation and a sufficient u-v coverage.

We note that the use of the non-standard band 8 is justified by the 
saving of exposure time because of the significantly larger flux of this 
very faint object in this band 8 compared to other bands (e.g.,band 7). 
</prj:justificationText>
